.SH C) TABLE FORMAT
the library defines the table structure to be built into the program.  it is
simple, but i want to avoid trivial issues that come from re-defining it.

.nf
struct cSCORE_TABLE {
   char        s_label     [LEN_TERSE];
   char        s_default;
   char        s_sample;  
   char        s_print     [LEN_LABEL];  
   char        s_desc      [LEN_DESC];
   char        s_valid     [LEN_TITLE];
   char        s_legend    [LEN_FULL];
};

.RS 3
.B char* <label> is an unique, uppercase 0-12 character line identifier.
.RE

.RS 3
.B char  <default> is the starting value for that position.
.RE

.RS 3
.B char  <sample> is a realistic, most common value for that entry
.RE

.RS 3
.B char  <print> is a 1-6 character title for report headers
.RE

.RS 3
.B char  <desc> is a 1-50 character description of the entries purpose
.RE

.RS 3
.B char  <valid> is a 0-30 character set of valid characters for this entry
.RE

.RS 3
.B char  <legend> is a 0-200 character explanation of the valid characters
.RE

.SH D) SETUP
once the table is created in the source code, it is simple to create and
destroy.

.SS char  ySCORE_init (<table>, <valiidate>, &<handle>)
accepts the table name and returns a handle to the malloced object.

.RS 3
.B char <validate> 'y' means check marks against the valid field, any other
value and it skips validity checks.
.RE

.SS char  ySCORE_wrap (&<handle>)
frees the data and grounds the pointer.


